doc.after: The area of Chew Stoke is surrounded by arable land and dairy farms on the floor of the Chew Valley It is located along the Strode Brook tributary of the River Chew on the northwest side of the Chew Valley Lake While much of the area has been cleared for farming trees line the tributary and many of the roads The village is built along the main thoroughfare Bristol Road which runs northeast to southwest An older centre is located along Pilgrims Way which loops onto Bristol Road and features an old stone packhorse bridge now pedestrianised and a 1950s Irish bridge used as a ford in winter 5 Houses line both of these roads with residential cul de sacs and lanes extending from them
